The venue is small. However, outdoor seating is available for 2 groups. The food in my opinion is mediocre. We ordered the patties( chicken & vegetables) and did the price did not align with the size and portion ( 2 bite size pieces). I ordered the fish dish( slice of king fish topped with carmelized  onions with seasoned rice). Again, it didn't align with the cost. The rice lacked savor and the fish simply didnt speak tasty. The carmelized onions was the only part that I would go crazy for. My fried ordered goat with seasoned rice and she loved it. I did love the pepper sauce that accompanied the orders. The menu didn't offer many options. The hostess was very pleasant and inviting. She was supersweet. Cheers All!
The food is absolutely delicious and the owners are very friendly and hospitable!! I will be visiting this restaurant more often. I definitely recommend this place to anyone looking for great food!!

Really great food, if you can handle the spice. Non spicy options also available ! Still my favorite African restaurant on 116th St between Frederick Douglass and Malcolm X. Their goat dish is the go-to but I've also tried their chicken dishes (mango one, spicy one, etc.) And they're all solid dishes, including their sambusas (which reminds me of Indian samosas). I also love their spiced milk tea, and want to try their ginger infused coffee next time. Nice people too.

The food here is scrumptious and absolutely delicious! This is a hidden gem found in Harlem.  Try the white grapefruit soda and the lamb with rice on your first try!  The owners are super friendly and love to share their food and culture :)

I had the hilib ari $18 and chicken sugar $15 because that was one of the only items available. I dont know how this place has decent reviews. It tasted very similar to bland Indian food. I will definitely not be returning.

I went there for my adult son (he wanted to eat there for his birthday). The food was delicious considering that it was a Somalia Restaurant (acttually, it was a take out). The place was design to seat about 25 customers and the place was spotless. Highly recommended to go and eat there.

A nice little place in Harlem, with really great food and delicious beverages.  I was pleasantly surprised with a good sized portion of beef suqaar with a side of yellow rice spiced with notes of cinnamon and topped with sultanas.  The drinks were served in little Mason style jars and were pulled with ice, perfect for an unusually warm summer day.  An excellent place to recharge!
Very delicious. A great mixture of spices and I loved the idea of bringing your own bottle.

*Update: Returned to Safari Restaurant...found many improvements. STILL provided quality customer service. The Food is the best i had and a while. The only East African restaurant my wife and I found in New York. If you are looking to taste some new but yet delicious, give Safari Restaurant a try.

Wish my goat dish had more sauce but the flavor was excellent. Very friendly service and acceptable wait time for food. Visit and enjoy this unique experience.

Recommendations: sabaayad, goat dish, busketti (beef), also chicken curry.  Fried dessert and qaxwo (coffee with ginger). Simple interior that showed character...Will return! Excellent value. BYOB.

the staff were warm, attentive , and friendly. New to Somali food I now know where to go to have Somali food. the drinks were great as well. intimate friendly setting. Plus the Somali music was great to hear!

The food here is amazing, and the people working there/the owners are even nicer. It is such a great experience going there every time!!! It's BYOB (with no corking fee). It almost feels like you are going to meet family when you go there, with amazing food!!!
Definitely get the beef sambusas. Food was pretty good but service was slow.
Great.
Really interesting cuisine, but no way to avoid carbs, so a limited menu. BYOB from the Winery, which is a staple shop for me, so a great combination.

If you go to this place don't expect to be impressed. I asked a suggestion to waitress and I ordered Hilib Ari and a tea per her suggestion. The service was pretty slow. When I asked a question, the waitresses did not bother to stop their chat to answer the question. There were just 3 tables to attend and they were too busy to attend customers. The waitress forgot to bring the tea, which I was planning to have while I was waiting for my meal. I had to remind waitress to fetch the tea. Somali tea was OK, though it taste like a very sweetened regular tea. Hilib Ari tasted good but the portion was small and one third of the meat was bone. Don't go to this place if you are very hungry. The rice was not special, but tasted OK. If I've tasted the best they can offer I don't recommend anybody to visit this place.
The food was absolutely amazing and the light green sauce they served on the side with each dish was lovely with a refreshing lime and hit of spice.

This hole-in-the-wall Somali restaurant serves up a refreshing berry and hibiscus juice (fiimto) along with fried triangle dough (sambuusas), not unlike the Indian samosas.  We also enjoyed the chicken suqaar, a traditional Somali dish with Basmati rice. The proprietor also gave us a banana each to go with our meals, apparently a Somalian tradition. It doesn't seem out of place and even enhanced our dining experience!

(Translated by Google) The food is quite good, prices are reasonable for the area. We had a very pleasant time, we were alone and we could have dinner with tranquility, listening to traditional Somali music. Very different from what it would be to eat a hamburger in a typical American place, with all the noise that that implies. Mango curry is the star option !!! Tea is wonderful too, but better without sugar ...  (Original) La comida está bastante bien, los precios son razonables para la zona. Hemos pasado un rato muy agradable, estábamos sólos y pudimos cenar con tranquilidad, escuchando música tradicional Somalí. Muy distinto de lo que sería comer una hamburguesa en sitio típico Americano, con todo el ruido que eso supone. Curry de mango es la opción estrella!!! El té es maravilloso también, pero mejor sin azúcar...

By far the BEST east African food I've had in the states!!! Authentic east african dishes that transport you to the sweet tastes(not spicy) and smells of Africa. If you're looking for high quality, delicious, authentic east african food and experience this IS the place to go. Food was SOOO GOOD! Definitely returning.
Small and cosy spot...oh and the food was delicious.
My first time having Somali food. Jesus Christ it was amazing here.
Lunch of goat and rice (Hilib Ari) was good. Mango juice was also good. Berry and Hibiscus juice (Fiimto) was great. People were friendly.
Amazing food. Flavorful, fresh, and has the right amount of spice. Highly suggest the tea. Definitely go again.

Great bakery that actually opens LATE! Hard to find a bakery that stays open pass 6-7 pm.  Small little bake shop with a ton of cupcakes, cakes, and pies to pick from.  Mini Cupcakes - $1.75 each - I tried the Red Velvet, Carrot, and Peanut Butter Fudge Swirl. Very moist cakes. Each cupcake was done just right. Love that they have minis so you can try a bunch.  Cherry Cheesecake, slice - $5 - Very creamy cheesecake with a great crust. Junior's was a little better though.  Boo me! I forgot to take pictures of the desserts before we ate everything!
The food was amazing and we have been welcome in such a warm way! like this place!

Are you up for some deliciously flavorful, savory spices? Look no further. This place has a small menu, but the promising smells of cardamom, cinnamon, and cloves hit you the moment you come in the door. The food was inexpensive and well-prepared, and the decor was pleasant. If this place is empty, it's because not enough people have given it a try!
